	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>If <latex>S,T\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[2]</latex>, respectively, are represented by</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
A = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 & -1 & 7 \\
4 & 1 & 6
\end{array}
\right]\quad \text{and} \quad 
B = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 6 & 11 \\
3 & -4 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>find the matrix representing <latex>S+T</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<approach>
			<answer>
				<para><latex>(S+T)</latex> is represented by</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A + B = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 & 5 & 18 \\
7 & -3 & 7
\end{array}
\right]
					]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</answer>
			<solution.hint>
				<para>Review the 
					<subordinate>
						<hot>proposition</hot>
						<crossref>
							<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_SumLinearTrafos"/>
							<para>Look up this result</para>
						</crossref>
					</subordinate>
					which shows that <latex>S+T</latex> is linear, and what its representing  matrix is.</para>
			</solution.hint>
			<solution>
				<para>We <subordinate>
					<hot>know</hot>
					<crossref>
						<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_SumLinearTrafos"/>
						<para>Look up this result</para>
					</crossref>
				</subordinate> that <latex>(S+T)</latex> is linear and that it is represented by the matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A} + \Mtrx{B}</latex>. Thus we compute</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
\aligned
A +B\ &=\  
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
2 & -1 & 7 \\
4 & 1 & 6
\end{array}
\right]\ + \ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 6 & 11 \\
3 & -4 & 1
\end{array}
\right] \\
&=\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
0 & 5 & 18 \\
7 & -3 & 7
\end{array}
\right]
\endaligned
					]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</solution>
		</approach>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>If <latex>L\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[4]</latex> is represented by</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
C = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
4 & 1 & 6 \\
2 & -1 & 7 \\
9 & 3 & -11 \\
-1 & 2 & 5
\end{array}
\right]
					]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>find the matrix representing <latex>4\cdot L</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<approach>
			<answer>
				<para><latex>(4\cdot L)</latex> is represented by</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
4\cdot C = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
16 & 4 & 24 \\
8 & -4 & 28 \\
36 & 12 & -44 \\
-4 & 8 & 20
\end{array}
\right]
					]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</answer>
			<solution.hint>
				<para>Review the 
					<subordinate>
						<hot>proposition</hot>
						<crossref>
							<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_ScalarProductLinearTrafo"/>
							<para>Look up this result</para>
						</crossref>
					</subordinate>
					which shows that <latex>t\cdot L</latex> is linear for every <latex>t</latex> in <latex>\RNr</latex>, and what its representing  matrix is.</para>
			</solution.hint>
			<solution>
				<para>We <subordinate>
					<hot>know</hot>
					<crossref>
						<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_ScalarProductLinearTrafo"/>
						<para>Look up this result</para>
					</crossref>
				</subordinate> that <latex>(4\cdot L)</latex> is linear and that it is represented by the matrix <latex>4\cdot \Mtrx{C}</latex>. Therefore we compute</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
\aligned
4\cdot C\ &=\ 
4\cdot \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
4 & 1 & 6 \\
2 & -1 & 7 \\
9 & 3 & -11 \\
-1 & 2 & 5
\end{array}
\right] \\
&=\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
16 & 4 & 24 \\
8 & -4 & 28 \\
36 & 12 & -44 \\
-4 & 8 & 20
\end{array}
\right]
\endaligned
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
			</solution>
		</approach>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>You are given linear maps <latex>S\from \RNr\to \RNr[3]</latex>, <latex>S(x)=(2x,5x,-x)</latex> and <latex>T\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr</latex>, <latex>T(x,y,z)=x-y+2z</latex>. Find the matrix representing <latex>T\Comp S</latex>.</para>
		</problem>
		<approach>
			<answer>
				<para><latex>T\Comp S</latex> is represented by</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>\Mtrx{A} = [-5]</latex>
				</math.display>
			</answer>
			<solution.hint>
				<para>Review the 
					<subordinate>
						<hot>proposition</hot>
						<crossref>
							<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_CompositeLinearTrafos"/>
							<para>Look up this result</para>
						</crossref>
					</subordinate>
					which shows that <latex>T\Comp S</latex> is linear for every <latex>t</latex> in <latex>\RNr</latex>, and what its representing  matrix is.</para>
			</solution.hint>
			<solution>
				<para>We <subordinate>
					<hot>know</hot>
					<crossref>
						<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_CompositeLinearTrafos"/>
						<para>Look up this result</para>
					</crossref>
				</subordinate>
					that <latex>T\Comp S\from \RNr \to \RNr</latex> is linear. So we may compute the <latex>(1,1)</latex>-matrix representing <latex>T\Comp S</latex> as the product of the matrices representing <latex>T</latex> and <latex>S</latex> individually. The matrix representing <latex>S</latex> is</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
\Mtrx{A}\ :=\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
2 \\ 5 \\ -1
\end{array}
\right]
						]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Moreover, the matrix representing <latex>T</latex> is</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>\Mtrx{B} := [1\ \ -1\ \ 2]</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Therefore <latex>T\Comp S</latex> is represented by</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
\aligned
\Mtrx{B}\cdot \Mtrx{A}\ &=\ 
[1\ \ -1\ \ 2]\cdot
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
2 \\ 5 \\ -1
\end{array}
\right] \\
&=\ 
[-5]
\endaligned
						]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</solution>
		</approach>
		<approach>
			<solution>
				<para>Another way of answering this problem is to compute the effect of <latex>T\Comp S</latex> on <latex>x</latex> in <latex>\RNr</latex> first, and then finding the representing matrix:</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>T\Comp S(x) = T(2x,5x,-x) = 2x-5x-2x = -5x</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Therefore <latex>(T\Comp S)</latex> is represented by the <latex>(1,1)</latex>-matrix <latex>[-5]</latex>.</para>
			</solution>
		</approach>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the linear transformations <latex>\RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> below find the matrix representing it.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L</latex> doubles the length of each vector <latex>\Vect{x}\in \RNr[2]</latex> and then rotates it about the origin through an angle of 150 degrees in the counterclockwise direction.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para><latex>L</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
-\sqrt{3} & -1 \\
1 & -\sqrt{3}
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>The columns of the matrix representing <latex>L</latex> are given by</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\aligned
L(1,0) &= 2(\cos(5\pi/6),\sin(5\pi/6)) &= 2\left( -\sqrt{3}/2 , 1/2 \right) \\
L(0,1) &= 2(\cos(8\pi/6),\sin(8\pi/6)) &= 2\left( -1/2 , -\sqrt{3}/2 \right)
\endaligned
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					
					<para>Here we have used that 150 degrees is <latex>5\pi/6</latex> radians. Thus <latex>L</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
-\sqrt{3} & -1 \\
1 & -\sqrt{3}
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L</latex> projects each vector  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> orthogonally onto the line <latex>y=x</latex> and then quarters its length.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para>The matrix representing <latex>L</latex> is</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\dfrac{1}{8}
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1 \\
1 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>The columns of the matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> representing <latex>L</latex> consist of <latex>L(\StdBss{1})=(1,0)</latex> and <latex>L(\StdBss{2})=(0,1)</latex>. To find these vectors, we first find the projection <latex>P</latex> of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> onto the line <latex>x=y</latex>.</para>
					
					<para>A normal vector to the line <latex>x=y</latex> is <latex>\Vect{n}:=(-1,1)</latex>. Therefore</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>P(x,y)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(x,y) - \dfrac{ \DotPr{(x,y)}{(-1,1)} }{ \DotPr{(-1,1)}{(-1,1)} } \cdot (-1,1)</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(x,y) - \dfrac{-x + y}{2}\cdot (-1,1)</right>
					</computation>
					
					<para>Therefore</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>P(1,0)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(1,0) - \tfrac{-1}{2}(-1,1) = \tfrac{1}{2} (1,1)</right>
						<left>P(0,1)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,1) - \tfrac{1}{2} (-1,1) = \tfrac{1}{2}(1,1)</right>
					</computation>
					
					<figure>
						<img src="ims/Prjctn_Exrcs.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
					</figure>
					<para>Now we need to contract these vectors by a factor of <latex>1/4</latex>:</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>L(1,0)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>\tfrac{1}{8}(1,1)</right>
						<left>L(0,1)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>\tfrac{1}{8}(1,1)</right>
					</computation>
					
					<para>Therefore the matrix representing <latex>L</latex> is</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\dfrac{1}{8}
\left[
\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1 \\
1 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the linear transformations <latex>\RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex> below find the matrix representing it.</para>
		</problem>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L\from \RNr[3] \to \RNr[3]</latex> dilates each vector <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> by a factor of <latex>3/2</latex> and then projects it orthogonally onto the <latex>yz</latex>-plane. </para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para><latex>L</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\dfrac{3}{2}
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>The matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> representing the dilation <latex>D</latex> is</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
A = \dfrac{3}{2}
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>The orthogonal projection <latex>P</latex> of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> onto the <latex>yz</latex>-plane satisfies</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>P(x,y,z) = (0,y,z)</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Consequently <latex>P</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
B = 
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>The transformation <latex>L = P\Comp D</latex> is</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
B\cdot A = \left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]\dfrac{3}{2}
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right] = 
\dfrac{3}{2}
\left[
\begin{array}{ccc}
0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		
		
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L</latex> shears each vector <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> parallel to the <latex>xy</latex>-plane with shear vector <latex>\Vect{s}=(-3,-1,0)</latex> and then reflects <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> through the origin.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para><latex>L</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 0 & 3 \\
0 & -1 & 1 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>The shear transformation <latex>S</latex> leaves the basic vectors <latex>\StdBss{1}</latex> and <latex>\StdBss{2}</latex> unchanged, and transforms <latex>\StdBss{3}</latex> into <latex>(-3,-1,1)</latex>. Therefore it is represented by the matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> below.</para>
					
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\Mtrx{A} := \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & -3 \\
0 & 1 & -1 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					
					<para>The reflection <latex>R</latex> through the origin sends every vector <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> to <latex>-\Vect{x}</latex>. Therefore it is represented by the matrix <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex> below.</para>
					
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\Mtrx{B} := \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					
					<para>As <latex>L=R\Comp S</latex>, the matrix representing <latex>L</latex> is</para>
					
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\Mtrx{B}\Mtrx{A} = \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & -1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & -3 \\
0 & 1 & -1 \\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right] =
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 0 & 3 \\
0 & -1 & 1 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		
		
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para><latex>L</latex>  first rotates , when viewed from the positive <latex>y</latex>-direction, through an angle of 60 degrees clockwise about the <latex>y</latex>-axis, then reflects <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> orthogonally through the <latex>xy</latex>-plane.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para><latex>L</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\dfrac{1}{2} \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & -\sqrt{3} \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
-\sqrt{3} & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				
				<solution>
					<para>The angle <latex>\theta:=\pi/3</latex> corresponds to 60 degrees. Now the rotation <latex>R</latex> has the following effect on the basic vectors</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>R(\StdBss{1})</left>
						<center>=	<info><para>To see this, draw a sketch, with the <latex>y</latex>-axis pointing toward you, the <latex>x</latex>-axis then points to the left, and the <latex>z</latex>-axis points upward.</para></info></center>
						<right>(\cos\theta , 0 , \sin\theta)</right>
						<left>R(\StdBss{2})</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,1,0)</right>
						<left>R(\StdBss{3})</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(-\sin\theta, 0 , \cos\theta)</right>
					</computation>
					
					<para>Therefore the matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> representing <latex>R</latex> is</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
A := \dfrac{1}{2} \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & -\sqrt{3} \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
\sqrt{3} & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					
					<para>The reflection <latex>T</latex> through the <latex>xy</latex>-plane has</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>T(\StdBss{1})</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(1,0,0)</right>
						<left>T(\StdBss{2})</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,1,0)</right>
						<left>T(\StdBss{3})</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,0,-1)</right>
					</computation>
					
					<para>Therefore the matrix <latex>\Mtrx{B}</latex> representing <latex>T</latex> is</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
B := \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					
					<para>As <latex>L=T\Comp R</latex>, it is represented by the matrix</para>
					
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
BA := \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right] \dfrac{1}{2} \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & -\sqrt{3} \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
\sqrt{3} & 0 & 1
\end{array}
\right] =
\dfrac{1}{2} \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 0 & -\sqrt{3} \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
-\sqrt{3} & 0 & -1
\end{array}
\right]
							]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>Given linear transformations</para>
			<para align="center"><latex>R\from \RNr[q]\to \RNr[p]</latex>, &nbsp; <latex>S\from \RNr[p]\to \RNr[n]</latex>, &nbsp;<latex>U\from \RNr[p]\to \RNr[n]</latex>, and <latex>T\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>,</para>
			<para>answer the questions below.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem>
