	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>A linear transformation <latex>T\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> satisfies</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>T(1,2) = (-2,2) \quad \text{and} \quad T(-1,3) = (-1,2)</latex>
			</math.display>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem><para>Find <latex>T(0,5)</latex>.</para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<computation>
						<left>T(0,5)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(-3,4)</right>
					</computation>
				</answer>
				<solution.hint>
					<para>One way to solve this problem is by noticing that</para>
					<computation>
						<left>(0,5)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(1,2) + (-1,3)</right>
					</computation>
					<para>Now compute, using the information that <latex>T</latex> is linear.</para>
				</solution.hint>
				<solution.hint>
					<para>Given that <latex>(0,5) = (1,2) + (-1,3)</latex>, we know that</para>
					<computation>
						<left>T(0,5)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>T(1,2) + T(-1,3)</right>
					</computation>
				</solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem><para>Find <latex>T\Comp T(0,5)</latex></para></problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<computation>
						<left>T\Comp T(0,5)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,2)</right>
					</computation>
				</answer>
				<solution.hint>
					<para>Look for numbers <latex>r</latex> and <latex>s</latex> such that</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>T(0,5) = (-3,4) = r\cdot (1,2) + s\cdot (-1,3)</latex>
					</math.display>
				</solution.hint>
				<solution.hint>
					<para><latex>(0,5) = (-1)\cdot (1,2)\ +\ 2\cdot (-1,3)</latex></para>
				</solution.hint>
				<solution>
					<para>From part a) we know that <latex>T(0,5)=(-3,4)</latex>. To be able to apply the given information</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>T(1,2) = (-2,2) \quad \text{and} \quad T(-1,3) = (-1,2)</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>we look for numbers <latex>r</latex> and <latex>s</latex> such that</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>T(0,5) = (-3,4) = r\cdot (1,2) + s\cdot (-1,3)</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>This is a system of two linear equations with two variables. It has the unique solution</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>T(0,5) = (-3,4) = (-1)\cdot (1,2) + 2\cdot (-1,3)</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Therefore,</para>
					<computation>
						<left>T\Comp T(0,5)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>T( (-1)\cdot (1,2) + 2\cdot (-1,3) )</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>- T(1,2) + 2\cdot T(-1,3)</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>-(-2,2) + 2\cdot (-1,2)</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(0,2)</right>
					</computation>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
